{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_herring_ver01/data/sn83045499/00393342341/1938021601/0370.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Alaska Empire\nPublished every evening except Sunday by the\nEMPIRE PRINTING COMPANY\nat Second and Main Streets. Juneau. Alaska.\nEntered in the Post Office In Juneau as Second Class Matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES.\n\u2022ftivered by carrier in Juneau and Doualas for St.2S per month.\nBy mail, postage paid, at the following rates:\nOne year, in advance $12 00; six months, in advance. $6 00\n0DC bub^nJrs \"wU?confer If\u2019favor if they will promptly notify\nme Business Office ci Bny failure or irregularity in the de\nj m i <1 [i cir papers.\nie.eni ft'.- New! Office. 602: Business Office. 374.\nMP'*BFn Ol ASSOCIATED PRESS.\n\u25a0j>.f o Prc\". Is exclusively entitled to the use for\nl e-' M'ciii ,o'i ol all news dispatches credited to it or not\notherwise credited in this paper and ulso the local news\npublished herein. _\nALASKA CIRCULA'I ION GUARANTEED TO HE LARGER\nTHAN THAI OF ANY OTHER PUBLICATION\nX r\nKEEPING BtlSINESS ON AN EVEN\nKEEL IN JUNEAU\nIn connection with the President's recent mes\nsage to Congress asking for $250,000,000 to take care\nof relief needs for the next four months. WPA offi\ncials. in emphasizing the need for public appropria\ntion. announced that three million persons had been\nlaid off from their jobs in the last three months.\nTo Alaska that means a great deal more than\nthe cold report would indicate. It means that the\nunemployment situation in the States is likely to\noverflow into the Territory unless the campaign of\neducation now undertaken by Juneau and other cities\nand organizations throughout Alaska that there are\nno jobs available here lor Outside workmen is pushed.\nMany of those jobless men, with nothing in sight in\nthe States, are going to head north, spending, perhaps,\ntheir last few dollars to do so, unless we can carry\non a full-throated campaign to discourage them.\nIt isn't that Alaska does not want population\nand industry. It does. It needs both to carry forward\nits natural development. But it must have in that\nnew population persons who are equipped to come\nto the Territory and care for themselves for at least\na year until they get adjusted. If there are persons\nso fixed among the unemployed now reported in the\nStutes. Alaska welcomes them. But the unfortunate\nfact is that most of those from the Outside seeking\nwork in the Territory are not financially able to care\nfor themselves without some kind of employment.\nAnd there is no extra employment to be iound in the\nnorth at this season of the year.\nEvery mail brings The Empire from one to a\nhalf dozen or more inquiries from persons in the\nStates asking if they can get a job in Alaska. Most\nof them no doubt are honest, conscientious and sin\ncere Americans looking for an opportunity to make\na livelihood. But their letters show clearly that they\nmust hive employment almost at once when they\narrive here to care for themselves. And. of course,\nas we in the know, that cannot be guar\nanteed or even ventured for the simple fact that\nAlaska jobs are filled up. Filled up to overflowing,\nas our own unemployment situation in Juneau glar\ningly reveals.\nIn view of this condition, and for the benefit of\nboth those without means Outside and our own Alaska\nworkmen, it falls to the lot of every one of uc to\nemphasize the true conditions here in every contact\nwe make in the States.\nIn arriving at the foregoing conclusion, it is apro\npos for most of us in the north to compare conditions\nhere with those reported from the Outside. Juneau\nis a fair example Here we have the largest year\naround industrial payroll in the Territory. Month\nafter month it pours into our marts of trade, giving\nthe city a substantial backlog of business. The wages\nare above comparable pay scales in the States. And\nthey are perpetual.\nBy keeping on an even keel, we can avoid such\neconomic disaster as is reported befalling many in\ndustrial centers Outside at this time. Business here\nis good. But to keep it that way we must continue to\ndo business in normal fashion and take advantage of\ntoe fortunate condition which is ours.\nALASKA AVIATION ADVANCE\nThe progress that Alaska is making in the air is\ngraphically revealed in the report of the Alaska Aero\nnautics and Communications Commission published\nyesterday in The Empire. The report shows that 21\nairplane companies, operating an average of 67 planes\nduring the six months ending with December, carried\n13 238 passengers and 1.792.559 pounds of freight and\nexpress as well as 117.351 pounds of mail.\nA previous Customs report revealed that during\nthe entire year of 1937. there were 101 planes operat\ning in the Territory, which carried more than 20.958\npassengers and more than three million pounds of\nfreight and express.\nAviation is big business in Alaska. Every year it\ngrows larger. Prom eight planes operating m 1929.\nit jumped to 101 in the year just past with business\nin accordance. There probably is no single ousiness\nin the north doing more toward further development\nof the Territory than aviation. It is one of the great\ntransportation agencies that Alaska must have to\ngo forward.\nRegularly scheduled air connection with Seattle,\nmore airports and improvements of the present and\nadditional aids to aerial navigation are the next steps\nneeded so that aviation can continue its excellent\nwork. Congress can do well to heed the appeal of\nDelegate Dimond for financial aid to carry on the\nprogram.\nToday's forecast: Snow, followed by the Ski tour\nnament Sunday, followed by rain, followed by spring.\nThere\u2019s something about those \u201crecession\" cries\nin the States that remind us of a ball player caught\nbetween third and home with the winning run, who\nfailed to heed the advice of the third base line coach.\n\u201cFirst in War, First in Peace\u201d\nf Recruiting News)\nfew Americans bated war so much as clid George\nWashington. But he was not ail avowed, pcace-at\nnny-price pacifist who would have sacrificed National\nhonor and American self respect at the cost of a pusil\nlanimous, craven knuckling under\" when the cause\nfor taking up arms was just.\nOne has but to glance even casually over the\nwritten record left behind by the First President to\nDarn Washingtons heartfelt sentiments, And the\nmore one goes to Washington's letters and speeches\nand uncovers these gems of advice on the preservation\ncf an honorable peace, the more does one begin to\nfeel that the father of our country must have indeed\nteen endowed with a prophetic vision. At times\nWashington's words are almost uncanny when one\nconsiders them in the light of present-day world\naffairs and as those affairs affect our country.\nProbably the best known and most universally\nquoted of Washington'.* treatises upon this subject of\npreserving American peace with honor is the extract\nfrom his Farewell Address upon leaving public life:\n\"That we may always be prepared for war. but\nnever unsheath the sword except in self defense, so\nlong as justice, and oui essential rights and national\nrespectability, can be preserved without it.\u201d\nIn order to appreciate fully the significance of\nthis particular utterance, one must remember that\nthe Farewell Address was made public in September.\n1796. at a time when there were wars and rumors\nof wars in the Old World, and there was universal\nand grave concern that the young American nation\nmight become involved as a party in the European\nconflicts.\nWashington was sincerely desirous of avoiding all\nsuch foreign attachments and entanglements. Every\nAmerican schoolboy of today knows that. He warned\n'he nation, time and again, of the risk. Witness, a\nletter under Washington's hand to Gouverneur Morris,\nwritten from Philadelphia three years before the Fare\nwell Address, in which Washington says, in part:\n\"Unwise should we be in the extreme to involve our\nselves in the contests of European nations, where our\nweight could be but small though the loss to ourselves\nwould be certain.\u201d\nWhen, in 1917. American soldiers stepped on\nEuropean soil to participate in a European war for\nthe first time in our national history, the situation\nwas such as even Washington the far-seeing could not\nby any stretch of even his gifted imagination have\nforeseen. Then in 1917 there was a principle of demo\ncratic sovereignty involved- a sharp issue in which\nthe fate not only of our own American democracy was\nat stake but the democracy of the entire civilized\nfamily of world-wide nations. There can be no doubt\nat all bul that the First President, had he been in a\nposition to have sat in judgment, would have heartily\napproved of our action in France in the World War.\nJust, because the precedent was set, in 1917. how-\never, is no surety that it will become an established\ncustom. Tlie warning left by Washington of the grave\ndangers involved in any foreign entanglements re\nmains with Americans to this day and will be soberly\nadhered to, one may feel certain.\nPreserving that world-wide respect, that typically\nAmerican, highly cherished spirit ol isolation, calls for\na constant, guard and preparation. And as Washing\nton has so aptly pointed out in a speech to Congress\non January 8. 1790:\n\"A free people ought not only to be armed, but\ndisciplined.\u201d\nIn another thoughtful address to the Congress, on\nDecember 3. 1793. he said:\n\"I cannot recommend to your notice measures for\nthe fulfilment of our duties to the rest of the world\nwithout again pressing upon you the necessity ol\nplacing ourselves in a condition of complete defense.\nThe United States ought not to indulge a persuasion\nthat, contrary to the order of human events, they will\nforever keep at a distance those painful appeals to\narms with which the history of every other nation\nabounds.\n\"There is a rank due to the United States among\nnations, which will be withheld, if not absolutely\nlost, by the reputation of weakness. If we desire to\navoid insult, we must be able to repel it; if we desire\nto secure peace, one of the most powerful instruments\nof our rising prosperity, it must be known that we\narc at all times ready for war.\u201d\n\u201cIf we desire to secure peace it must be known\nthat we are at ail times ready for war.\u201d How appli\ncable are those words in this war-torn, war-threatened\nworld of 1938!\nWe Americans by long habit have become more\nand more in the guise of students sitting at the feet\nof the sage teacher, George Washington. He builded\nwell, and left many precepts and admonitions for\nAmericans of later generations to follow. Not keen\nfor war was this man tvho knelt unashamed in the\nsnow at Valley Forge to pray for an honorable, lasting\npeace. But well did he know that the price we must,\npay, for all time, oi that blessed and enduring peace\nwhich all true Americans seek, is adequate and com\nplete Preparedness. We feel sure that this natal\nmonth of Washington's birth is an apt time to review\nhis sober councils.\nThe Pension Game\n(Cincinnati Enquirer)\nThere can be no mistaking the dangers inherent\nin the scheme urged by veterans' organizations recent\nly before a committee of Congress. They are asking\nfor general pensions for widows and orphans of all\nWorld War veterans. They are not asking merely\npensions for widows and orphans of men who lost\ntheir lives in the service o\u2019 their country. These al\nready are being paid, and properly so.\nWhat we see is precisely what President Roosevelt\nwarned against when he vetoed the bonus bill several\nyears ago. In making that futile effort to prevent a\ntreasury raid, the President forecast that demands for\npensions would inevitably follow if the adjusted serv\nice certificates were paid in cash. Now It is working\nout precisely that way.\nThe widows and orphans of the men who gave\ntheir lives for their country deserve much of us. They\nnow receive pensions. Probably these pensions should\nbe increased. Their losses are great, and are directly\ndue to the World war. Generosity to these persons\nought to be a cardinal principle of public policy.\nBut just what claim on the Federal Treasury\ndoes a woman have who. after reading the proposed\nlaw. marries a healthy veteran in prosperous circuin\nstances, let us say in 1M8 and survives him? She\nmay even marry with the actual intent of becoming\na pensioner. In any case her husband suffered no\ninjury in the war and she did not even marry him\nuntil 20 years after the war. Her claim to a pension\nis utterly fantastic. It has its basis nowhere save in\nthe political power of the veterans' organizations\u2014\nthe power to raid the Treasury because they swing the\nweapon of the \"soldier vote.\u201d\nThe question at issue in this new proposal is two\nfold. It threatens a new and heavy drain on the\nFederal budget. It also poses the question whether\nveterans by playing politics can coerce the remainder\nof the people.\nAmbassador Hugh R. Wilson has departed for his\nnew post in Berlin. He probably will be happy there\nuntil he says what he thinks aboyt Hitler.\u2014Cleveland\nPlain Dealer.\nJapanese are reputed to like jokes 400 or 500 years\nild. The invasion of China is probably a sample.\u2014\nPhiladelphia Bulletin.\nBy and by. executives may be dropping in at the\nWhite House, who have no business elsewhere.\u2014\nBuffalo Courier-txpress.\nH A P P Y\n-B I R T H D A Y\nThe Emptre extends congratula\ntions and best wishes today, their\nbirthday anniversary, to the follow\ning:\nFEBRUARY 16, 1918\nKenneth Junge\nPercy E. Reynolds\nOlga Paul\nT. F. Garielson\nMrs. D. T. Dickinsen\nF. T. Rhody\nMODERN\nETIQUETTE\nBy Roberta Lee\nQ. If a married woman has re\n:ained her maiden name for busi\nness purposes, and then has a child,\nmay she still use her maiden name?\nA. Yes, for business purposes.\nQ. Are dishes ever served by the\nhead of lire tabic at a formal din\nner?\nA. No; the waiters or waitresses\nattend to this.\nQ. Is a large theatre party one\nrf the favorite entertainments giv\nrn for a debutante?\nA. Yes, it is popular.\nDAILY LESSONS\nIN ENGLISH\nBy W. L. Gordon\nWords Often Misused: Do not say,\nHelen is a tasty dresser.\" Say.\nHelen dresses tastefully.\u201d\nOften Mispronounced: Rendez\nvous. Pronounce ren-de-voo, a as\nin ah, e as in get unstressed, oo as\nn too, accent first sylable.\nOften Misspelled: Coercion. Ob\nserve the second c.\nSynonyms: Glad, gratified, hap\npy, pleased, delighted, joyful, cheer\nful, content.\nWord Study: \"Use a word three\ntimes and it is yours.\u201d Let us in\ncrease our vocabulary by mastering\none word each day. Today\u2019s word:\nAccede; to agree. \"They acceded to\nour terms.\u201d\nLOOK and LEARN\nBy A. C. Gordon\n1. Is the earth nearer to the sun\nin summer or in winter?\n2. What Biblical character\nbrough down fire from heaven?\n3. When were dental plates first\npatented in the United States?\n4. What was the cause of the\nsinking of the Titanic?\n5. Which country is the largest\nconsumer of sugar in the world?\nANSWERS\n1. In winter.\n2. Elijah.\n3. In 1840.\n4. Collision with an iceberg. The\nihip ran on a submerged shelf of\nice and ripped off a portion of her\nbottom in sliding off.\n5. The United States.\n\u201cMUSIC FOR MADAME\u201d\nSponsored by the Martha Society;\nat the Capitol Theatre. Tuesday eve\nning. February 22. adv.\nTry The Empire classifieds for\nresults.\nVISIT THE i\n\nS and A7\nFIVE ANT). TEN\n\u201cThe Store for\nMen\u201d\nj SABIN\u2019S\nFront St.\u2014Triangle Bldg, j\nGARBAGE HAULED\nReasonable Monthly Rates\nE. 0. DAVIS\nTELEPHONE 212\nPhone 47?3\n20 Years Ago\nFrom The Empire\nFEBRUARY 16. 1918\n\"Feathertop\" was the name of the\ninteresting play presented by the\ndramatic class of the Juneau High\nSchool under the supervision of Miss\nDresser. The leading role was played\nby Wilbur Burford, and Roberta\nCoryell and Jack Oswell were oth\ners in the cast.\nUnder a decision made by te De\npartment of the Interior all Natives,\nwho had become citizens, were to\nbe allowed the same privileges as\nregards the ownership of land as\nwere whites.\nPreparations were being made for\nthe celebration on the following day\nof the 80th birthday of Mrs. Jane\nClark, pioneer of Juneau. A family\nreunion was to be held at te home\nof her daughter. Mrs. Lily Burford.\nMrs. Jules B. Caro and Mrs. John\nT. Spickett. were other daughters\nof Mrs. Clark. Still hale and hearty\nin spite of her age, she was busy\nknitting sweaters for the Red Cross.\nShe had already completed 23.\nMr. and Mrs. j. N. Stoodv of\nTrad well returned from a five weeks\nvisit in Tacoma. Mr. Stoody, who\nwas the only 33rd degree Mason in\nAlaska, had gone out for the pur\npose of attending a meeting of\nShriners.\nV. I. Hahn, superintendent of the\nWhite Pass Yukon Route, W. C.\nBlanchard, chief clerk and D. A.\nMuirhead, assistant superintendent,\nwho had been in Juneau in con\nnection with the eight-hcur argu\nments, returned to their homes in\nSkagway.\nThe matter of recommending that\nmen serving as jurors in the Dis\ntrict Court be required to master\nthe gentle art of knitting and prac\ntice it while engaged in their duties\nwas informally discussed at a meet\ning of the Douglas Red Cross.\nDr. Weyerhorst had pronounced\nboth Joe Garn and Abel Anderson\n\"physically fit\" for service in the\nAmerican navy and they were pre\nparing to leave for the south to en\nlist.\nWeather Highest, 20: lowest 7:\nClear.\nELK INITIATION,\nANNIVERSARY TO\nBE HELD TONIGHT\nInitiation will be held by the\nBenevolent and Protective Order of\nElks at the regular meeting at 8\no'clock this evening in Elks Hall.\nNorman Banfield. Exalted Ruler,\nannounces that the seventieth an\nniversary of the founding of the Elks\nlodge is also to be observed tonight.\nFollowing the meeting, a Dutch\nlunch will be served.\nM. E. Monagle, District Deputy\nGrand Exalted Ruler, will address\nthe lodge on the significance of the\nanniversary.\nTWO NEW MEN NOW IN\nCHARGE, SEWARD GATEWAY\nLester Busey is now editor, and\nWayne Blue is business manager of\nthe Gateway, published three times\na week at Seward. The two men\nstep into the position held for a\nnumber of years by Editor E. F. Jes\nson' who is now in Fairbanks in\ncharge of the weekly edition of the\nFairbanks News-Miner. Busey has\nbeen in the publishing business to\nthe westward previously and Blue\nis an oldtime resident of the Res\nurrection Bay City.\n\n\u2666J1\u2014\nHospital Notes\nMrs. Samuel Johnson and son\nwere dismissed today from St. Ann's\nHospital.\nDorothy Scott, a medical patient,\nwas admitted to the Government\nHospital yesterday.\nJennie Thomas underwent a ma\njor operation at the Government\nhospital this morning.\nAlaska\u201d by Lester D. Henderson\ncm\nHoroscope\n\u201cThe stars incline\nbut do not compel\u2019'\nMingled good and evil signs are\nseen in the horoscope lor today\nOut adverse influences dominate.\nUnder this planetary government\nboth men and women are easily\ndepressed. Disappointments and\ndelays may be expected.\nSevere conflicts between indus\ntrialists and their employees are\nforecast. Capital is now under in\nfluence making for resistance and\nretaliatory measures in strike con\ntests.\nUnder this configuration aged per\nsons may be subject to unreasonable\ndemands from younger members of\ntheir families or from employees.\nThe servant problem will vex many\nwomen.\nMisuse of money by agents and\niinancial scandals are indicated.\nBooms in the stock market may\nbe expected as a result of fortu\nnate trade agreements with foreign\nnations.\nMany signs that usually precede\ngreat wars. are detected by the\nseers who foretell amazing events\nbefore the end of the year.\nFluctuations in money values will\nbe disturbing despite the improved\nbusiness outlook. A split in the\nBritish government will affect\nstocks.\nPersons whose birthdate it is have\nthe augury of a year of limited pros\nperity. They should be cautious\nregarding partnerships and should\nnot borrow money.\nChildren born on this day are us\nually keen and intuitive. They are\non the cusp of Aquarius aond Pisces\nand partake of traits common to\nboth signs.\nFrederick E Ives, inventor, was\nborn on this day 1856. Others who\nhave celebrated it as a birthday in\nclude Cardinal Taschereau, Canad\nian prelate. 1820: Rene Lachnec, in\nventor of the stethoscope, 1791.\n(Copyright i, 19381\nA church is being built in South\nwick, England, to the memory of\nmothers.\nTOP NOTCH!\nFOR FINE FOOD\nS Luncheons 5Cc\nDinners 65c\nBODDING TRANSFER\nMARINE PHONE I\nBUILDING 707\nRock\u2014Coal Hauling\nStove\u2014Fuel Oil Delivery\nThe Charles W. Carter\nMortuary\nFourth and Franklin Sts.\nPHONE 136\nHealth Foods Center\nBATTLE CREEK. HAUSER j\nAND OTHER DIETETIC j\nFOODS\n230 Franklin St.\nJuneau Telephone 62\nPERCY'S CAFE\nI\nIce Cream, Soft Drinks. Candy\nCOFFEE SHOP\nPercy Reynolds, Manager\nZ 0 R I C\nDRY CLEANING\nSoft\nWater\nWashing\nYour\nALASKA\nLAUNDRY\nPHONE 15\n\u201cThe Squibb\nStores of\nAlaska\u2019\u2019\n:f_\u201cI\nAlaska Federal Savings\nand Loan Association\nAccounts Insured Up to $5,000\nP. O. Box 2718-Phone 3\nOFFICE\u2014119 Seward St. k\nJuneau. Alaska 1\n4\nHARRY\nRACE\nDRUGGIST\nDirectory\nPROFESSIONAL\nFRATERNAL SOCIETIES\nGASTINEAU CHANNEL\nJ\nI I\nDRS. KASER FREEBURGER\nDENTISTS\nBlomgren Building\nPHONE 56\nHours 3 a.m. to 9 p.m.\nT\nDr. Charles P. Jenne\nDENTIST\nRooms 8 and 9, Valentine Bldg.\nTELEPHONE 176\n\n\nDr. Richard Williams\nDENTIST\nOFFICE AND RESIDENCE\nGOLDSTEIN BUILDING\nDr. Judson Whittier\nCHIROPRACTOR\nDrugless Physician\nOffice hours: 10-12. 1-5. 7-9\nRooms 2-3-4, Triangle Bldg.\n\u2019\u2019HONE 667\nDr. A. W. Stewart\nDENTIST\nHours 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.\nSEWARD BUILDING\nOffice Phone 469\nDR. H. VANCE\nOSTEOPATH i\nConsultation and examination I\nfree. Hours 10 to 12; 1 to 5;\n7 to 9:30 by appointment.\nGastineau Hotel Annex\nSouth Franklin St. Phone 177 j\nRobert Simpson, Opt.D.\nGraduate Los Angeles College\nof Optometry and\nOpthalmology\nGlasses Fitted Lenses Ground j\nv WHEN IN A HURRY\nCALL COLE FOR OIL\n34 plus or 27 gravity, in any\namount QUICK!\nCOLE TRANSFER\nPhone 3441 nr Night 554\nHave Your Eyes Examined by\nDr. Rae L. Carlson\nOPTOMETRIST\nOffice Ludwig Nelson\u2019s Jewelry\nShop Phone Green 331\nFINE\nWatch and Jewelry Repairing\nat very reasonable rates\nPAUL BL0EDH0RN\nS. FRANKLIN STREET\n----Cl\nON THE MEZZANINE\nHOTEL JUNEAU\nBEAUTY SHOP\nLYLAH\nContoure\nX-Er-Vac\nWILSON\nTelephone\n538\nS I G R I D S\nj BEAUTY SALON\n-YOUR APPEARANCE IS\nOUR RESPONSIBILITY\u201d\nShattuek Bldg. Phone 318\nJUNEAU\nMELODY HOUSE\nMusic and Electric Appliances\n(Next Gastineau Hotel)\nMrs. Pigg Phone 65\nAlaska Music Supply\nArthur M. Uggen, Manager\nPianos\u2014Musical Instruments\nand Supplies\nj Phone 206 122 W. Second\nTry the Empire classifieds for\nresults.\nB. P. O. ELKS meet\nevery Wednesday at 8\np.m. Visiting brothers\nwelcome. N. C. BAN\nFIELD, Exalted Ruler:\nM. H. SIDES, Secre\ntary.\nMOUNT JUNEAU I.onr.E NO. 147\nSecond and fourth\nMonday of each month\nin Scottish Rite Temple\nv//, beginning at 7:30 p.:n.\n\\y DANIEL ROSS. Wor\nshipful Master: JAMES W. LET\nVERS. Secretary.\nREBEKAHS\nPerseverance Lodge ino. Z A meets\nevery second and fourth Wednes\nday. I.O.O.F. Hall. BETTY MC\nCORMICK. Noble Grand; RUTH\nBLAKE. Secretary.\n\nGuy Smith i\nDRUGS j\n5\nJ PIJROLA REMEDIES\nJ J\nPRESCRIPTIONS CARE- 4\n4 FULLY COMPOUNDED\nI 4\nFront Street Next Coliseuai\n\nPHONE 97\u2014Free Delivery 4\n_ _^\n\"The Rexall Store\"\nyour\nReliable\npharmacists\ncompound\nprescrip\ntions.\nButler-Mauro Drug Co.\n\u2014--a\n\"Tomorrow's Styles\nToday\"\nJuneau's Own Store\n\nH. S. GRAVES\n\u201cThe Clothing Man\u201d\nHome of Hart Schaffner and\nMarx Clothing\n-a\nHollmann\u2019s Pharmacy\n201 Seward St. Phone 45\nPRESCRIPTIONS CAREFULLY\nCOMPOUNDED FROM\nFRESH DRUGS\n-f\nJ. B. WARRACK\nEngineers\u2014Contractors j\nJUNEAU\n1\n|3_____45\nCOME IN and SEE the NEW j\nSTROMBERG-CARLSON\nRADIOS\ni J. B. Burford Co.\n\u201cOur door step is worn by\nSatisfied Customers\u201d\nSPECIALIZING\nIn French\nand\nItalian\nDinners\nCAFE\n4\nLode and placer location notices\nfor sale at The Empire Office.\nEmpire classifieds pay.\nThe First National Bank\nJUNEAU\n\nCAPITAL\u2014$50,000\nSURPLUS\u2014$'100,000\n\nCOMMERCIAL AND SAVINGS\nACCOUNTS\nSAFE DEPOSIT BOXES\n2% Paid on\nSavings\nAccounts","height":"27712","width":"21792"}}
